Introduction

Public understanding of science is critical in times of crisis. The following analysis was conducted to examine the trajectory of COVID-19 in Miami-Dade County. For phased reopening, the White House has set guidelines for local municipalities in their Opening Up American Again report. In the report, it is highly suggested that:

  1. Local areas show a downward trajectory in the number of positive cases as a percent of total tests over a two-week period, and
  2. Local hospitals have capacity to handle all patients without crisis care.

The analysis begins by looking at the number of new positive cases each day and the number of total tests performed each day. The figures are presented together because as there is more testing, there are likely to be more positive test results. Therefore, the proportion of positive cases is also calculated. Given either a flat or increasing number of tests performed, the proportion of positive cases is the key metric to be used when looking at epidemic trajectory. It is recommended that this proportion not exceed 5%.

Finally, to ensure hospitals can meet demand without crisis care, the COVID-19 positive hospitalization census, COVID-19 positive ICU census, and COVID-19 positive ventilation census is plotted over time. Census refers to the number of COVID-19 positive patients in the hospital, ICU, and on ventilators, respectively, on a given day.

The data above show for each day since April 2: the number of positive COVID-19 tests, the number of negative COVID-19 tests, and the proportion of positive COVID-19 tests to total COVID-19 tests.

Total COVID-19 Tests by Day

We see the following pattern for the count of total tests. (shown on a log scale):

The average number of COVID-19 tests performed each day has increased from about 2,000 in early April to over 10,000 in July. On average, from 20 March until 29 August, there was an increase of approximately 86 addition tests performed each day over the previous day. This data is presented on a log scale.

Positive COVID-19 Tests by Day

We see the following pattern for the count of positive tests:

There was a general decrease in the number of new positive test results from early April until around May 18th, the day Miami-Dade County reopened. Afterwards, this trend flattened out and then increased. Over the past two weeks, there has been an average increase of 8 new additional positive cases each day. This is compared with 23 new additional positive cases each day from the previous analysis. A record high of 3571 for new positive cases was obtained on July 11th.

Positive COVID-19 Tests within the Past Two Weeks

In addition to the overall trend of positive COVID-19 tests shown above, we also show an enhanced view of the last two weeks.

Proportion of Positive Cases within Past Two Weeks

The proportion of positive COVID-19 tests for the past two weeks is:

During the 14-day period from 16 August to 29 August, there was a decrease in the proportion of positive COVID-19 cases reported in Miami-Dade County. During this time, there was an average change of -0.3% per day for new positive cases. However, over the past week, this proportion appears to be trending downwards. Given a flat or increasing number of tests performed, the proportion of positive tests obtained is the key metric for examining COVID-19 trajectory. The percentage of positive test results obtained has exceeded the 5% positive threshold recommended by the World Health Organization (WHO) for reopening.

Proportion of Positive COVID-19 Tests by Day

These are the proportions of positive COVID-19 tests for the since the start of April:

Overall, the proportion of positive test results out of all tests decreased significantly from over 20% in April to 5% on May 18th, the date Miami-Dade County reopened. After reopening, the proportion of positive tests has increased steadily, reaching the current average of over 20%. Additionally, the proportion of positive tests has been consistently greater than 10% since June 22nd. This number is function of test availability and the population being tested. Given a flat or increasing number of tests performed, an increase in the proportion of positive tests obtained points to evidence of increased COVID-19 community spread in Miami-Dade county.

The data above is COVID-19 hospital census data in Miami-Dade County for all dates with available data since April 2. These columns are: the number of patients hospitalized with COVID-19 (Hospitalized), the number of patients in intensive care with COVID-19 (ICU), the number of patients in intensive care with COVID-19 who are also on ventilators (Ventilated), the number of patients positive for COVID-19 that were admitted the previous day (AdmitPrevDay), the number of patients recovered from COVID-19 that were discharged the previous day (DischPrevDay), and the net admission of patients positive for COVID-19 the previous day (DeltaAdmit; a negative value means more recovered patients were discharged than sick patients admitted). There is a data error for the count ventilated on the 4th of June. We removed this point from the data before estimating the models shown below.

Hospital COVID-19 Census

We now show a census plot of hospitalizations, patients in ICU, and those in ICU on ventilators (shown on a log scale):

Overall, since mid-April, the number of COVID-19 positive patients in Miami-Dade County hospitals remained constant at around 700 people in hospitals until early June. The COVID-19 ICU census decreased from its reported peak of 285 on April 17th to around 100 as of June 6th. Overall, the number of COVID-19 patients on ventilators decreased from its highest point of 192 ventilated on April 22nd to around 60 on June 6th.

Since June 6th there has been a steady increase in hospitalizations, ICU bed use and people ventilated due to COVID 19. On July 21st, 2299 COVID-positive patients were hospitalized, a new high during the period analyzed. Additionally, on July 26th, 561 COVID-positive patients were in the ICU, the most recorded during the epidemic. Finally, on July 24th, Miami-Dade hit a record high for ventilations with 335 COVID-positive patients. This number may increase as ventilation tends to lag behind ICU admission. Note: data is plotted on a log scale.

Overall from March 16th to approximately May 25th in Miami-Dade County, there was a decrease in the number of deaths per day. The orange triangle depicts the county reopening date. The peak number of deaths so far reported was 30 on April 27th. This decrease in deaths may be attributable to advances in COVID-19 treatments and standard of care. A decrease in median age of those impacted could also partially explain this decrease.There has been a recent increase in deaths reported per day for Miami-Dade County.

Note: Due to delays in classifying the cause of death and thus of reporting deaths due to COVID-19, the most recent data will undercount the number of deaths. For this reason, the last five weeks were excluded from this analysis of deaths.

Conclusion

During the past two weeks, the number of positive COVID-19 tests obtained has increased by an average of 8 each day, which is a smaller increase than during the previous several weeks. The proportion of positive COVID-19 tests is now decreasing. Nevertheless, the proportion of positive tests it still well over the 5% recommended by the WHO.

On July 21st, 2299 COVID-positive patients were hospitalized, a new high during the period analyzed. Additionally, on July 26th, 561 COVID-positive patients were in the ICU, the most recorded during the epidemic. Finally, on July 24th, Miami-Dade hit a record high for ventilations with 335 COVID-positive patients. This number may increase as ventilation tends to lag behind ICU admission. Furthermore, there has been a rise in deaths reported per day for Miami-Dade County.
